text:
my brain is so full of things i want to write & share but it's scary putting my fingers to the keyboard when i don't know how it's going to turn out or whether people will relate to or even care about the things i have to say

i read audre lorde's your silence will not protect you recently & keep flicking back to highlighted paragraphs like this one

i think many of us can probably relate to this, can't we? we bottle things up because we're worried about what people will think of us or we're scared we'll make things worse. but in the long run, staying silent doesn't protect us from the very thing we're desperate to speak out against

here's a quote from chidera eggerue's what a time to be alone. i shared it a few months ago but i loved it so much & it's relevant here so i thought i'd share it again ðŸ˜ "to care is to be vulnerable. according to the world, it's not cool to be vulnerable; it's cool to be stoic, aloof and unconcerned, because to emotionally inept people, this shows resilience, strength of character and the oh-so-admirable quality of being eternally unbothered. but this is all wrong, because to be constantly 'unbothered' is to be dead inside

for a lot of people, caring means losing. these are the people who invest all their energy into performing instead of living, because to appear unbothered all the time, you must be in a constant state of pretence. don't aim to be like these people. they need more help than you think you do. but it is not your place to save them"

text:
true transformation in life happens when we are willing to really own our story.  there are pieces of our lives we would much rather keep hidden in a closet for no one to see.  itâ€™s easier that way, because no one knows.  but is it really easier?
.
.
.
i used to think it was easier too. however, it wasnâ€™t until i finally started talking about chapters in my life that iâ€™d rather keep hidden that change started to occur.  it wasnâ€™t until i realized my addiction to food stemmed from a lack of self love - me not believing i deserved happiness, health, and love.  it was me hiding behind the food, diet cokes and sweets when my emotions were out of control.  it wasnâ€™t until i recognized that i turn to food when iâ€™m anxious, embarrassed, stressed or scared that i was able to finally overcome it. .
.
.
it wasnâ€™t until i shared about being taken advantage of by a boss, someone i aspired to be like, that i realized my toxic relationships also stemmed from a lack of self love.  i then put a plan in place to heal and learn what it feels like to speak my worth, claim my value, and be ok with making people uncomfortable by setting appropriate personal boundaries.
.
.
.
iâ€™m not saying you need to share your story with the world. not at all. but i am telling you that if you truly want to change, heal, and finally reach those goals then you must be willing to explore what got you here.  sharing this in a sacred space built just for you and those on a similar journey is part of my calling.  i donâ€™t take it lightly, and i also donâ€™t take everyone in who asks because itâ€™s more important to me that i protect who i do let in.
.

text:
@tazzdavies91 originally posted this quote. follow her if you love this one cos she seriously sources the best quotes on her feed.

anyway this quote struck me because i was previously in an abusive relationship with someone who literally tried to beat the madness out of me. whenever i was acting like my crazy self i would pay for it. at the time i playfully ran away and thought it was a game. i was young and even the bruises i was left with weren't enough to keep me away. today i am in a loving relationship with a man who lets me be myself, even if it's a little too much for him. he sometimes gets annoyed but has never once laid a hand on me in over 11 years together. it really is a blessing from the universe that i found someone who can let me be myself and i am so grateful. the need to get married and have kids is often what is fed to us to look for in a relationship. for me i would rather have what i do right now than a family with a man who won't let me be me.

quote reads: fall in love with someone who enjoys your madness, not an idiot who forces you to be normal.

#quotestoliveby #quotes #inspiration #relationshipgoals #relationships #goals #couples #love #girls #guys #metoo #herstory #mentalhealth  #beyourself #selflove #likeforfollow

text:
long post alert!! when i released my debut book on 15th november this year it was a total dream come true and the culmination of 18 months work.
it wasn't written to show off, blame or criticise anyone, but to show its readers that they too could overcome any adversity they faced in their lives.
my book went to number 1 in an hour after it was released and i was overwhelmed to have had such amazing and generous feedback from so many people, including the talented and inspiring crew at @authors&co.
i felt totally on top of the world and on purpose. through my challenges i was able to leave other's inspired and in a better place, and this was my sole intention. 
on the monday the hate began from a few members of my closest family calling me a liar,  quibbling over dates and accusing me of being cruel and using my story to enhance my business interests. more over they then began to mention legal action and this stopped me in my tracks. 
it fucking terrified me and i felt totaly lost. 
having thought i was strong and  healed i was shocked at how sad, desolate and distraught i was. 
i didn't care that they called me a liar. i know my truth. i know all that happened to me and i know that i wrote my story from my perspective.
i knew that i wasn't being vindictive nor malicious yet was aware that my book would have upset some people who didn't share my views of people i wrote about, because frankly their experiences and relationships with them were so totally opposing to my own but i wrote my truth from the heart. 
i have never had anxiety but i guess this is what i had.
i  felt sick, couldnt eat, shook, over thought, cried and had a chronic fear of being alone.
in order to preserve my sanity i took my book off sale and hid for a week, crying and weak.
the love of my friends and husband got me through that week and i gave myself time to heal.
i considered why i had shared my story and what i wanted from it.
it wasnt money, fame or infamy. what i wanted was to inspire, empower and motivate you to believe in you and your future, in your potential.
so, its no secret is back tomorrow!
#warrior #survivors #metoo #endviolenceagainstwomenandgirls #memoir #writersofinstagram

text:
#metoo 
a terrified 11 year old amybeth feels she is now ready to share her story.
-
-
in a convenience store, in london. 
i was 11 years old the first time a man exposed himself to me behind the cash register on the counter.. while my own granddad stood beside me unaware of the horrific things this man was doing.
i was confused, i thought he had an itch.. his smile was sinister but i was young.
he was never caught. he ran like the coward that he was.
i thought something like that could never happen again.
-
-
i've been slut shamed, cat called, even grabbed multiple times since then, and every time it happens it becomes less of a big deal.
i began to be told that things like that are to be expected as i get older and that's just the way the world is.
how about no?
how about 
it's not what you wear
it's not about the strength you could've used to fight them off
it's not about if you said no.. it's about if you didn't say yes
it's not how you act
it's not how much alcohol you consume
it's not the way the world is
it's not your fault.
-
-
you do not need to come forward with your stories to stand with us in this discussion.
-
-
we all stand together in solidarity.
(i apologize for the photo.. it's all i have at the moment)

hannah is a force to be reckoned with: she is a globally celebrated comedian, writer, producer, and social justice warrior. her brilliant 2018 netflix series and live shows nanette won public and critical acclaim, both at home in australia, and abroad.

hannah is a passionate advocate for a number of causes, being active within lgbtqi advocacy and with organisations including the sacred heart mission. she recognises the importance of an intersectional lens in the perpetuation of privilege and disadvantage; and urges people to look beyond their own experience to unpack the role of gender, sexual identity, disability, and ethnicity in discrimination and abuse.

text:
this is not consent. 
as part of my senior show, the unspoken: voices of the voiceless, i did a performance piece regarding sexual assault. clothing is never an indication of consent to having sex. this is a social critique of victim blaming and the declaration that rape is justifiable dependent on the clothing worn during the assault.  no matter what an individual wears, they should never be subjected to rape, nor should they feel obligated to have sex.

in ireland, a 17 year old girl had her underwear used in a rape case with cousel saying "you have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front." during this performance, i wore underwear that matched this description. 
this needs to stop. 
#thisisnotconsent #dontfuckingtouchme #metoo #timesup #sexualassaultsurvivor #sexualassault #nomeansno #violenceagainstwomen #endrapeculture #stopviolence #mybodymychoice

this is the most current address i can find for cyntoia brown.

cyntoia brown #410593
tennessee prison for women
2 north b-49
3881 stewarts lane
nashville, tn 37218

if you have more relevant information on where to send her some support, or how to send money to her through jpay (bc it is not letting me, they say it is being blocked) please comment below. i would love to know how i can assist her. 
tw: generally stressful mention of rape at this point.

let's send our girl some love. i cannot imagine having to spend 2 decades locked up for murdering my rapist. this would leave me feeling incredibly hopeless. cyntoias' case has been instrumental in helping change certain policies about how tennessee handles child sexual abuse, but as we've seen this has done little to help her.  cyntoia has a documentary on pbs that i would strongly encourage you to watch. 
the best thing we can do right now is to petition #governorbillhaslam to grant clemency, despite his boards decision. we need to remind him directly that there is public pressure across the country about this case. we cannot just leave her there. 
cyntoia brown is a now famous example of how our country treats sex trafficking victims.

text: â€œclutchâ€ here are some detail shots her face i thought it would be nice to share with you. (some info from previous post-â€œclutchâ€ (life sized) from the avian show a few years ago. in her lap there is a little pile of bird skulls on a sheepskin. the skulls have been stained and gilded with metal leaf so they seem like a pile of dark jewels that she is playing with, fondling and perhaps protecting. her clutch of eggs. i see her as an expression of maternal and erotic self possession. i made her before the heat of the #metoo movement was on, and i have been thinking a lot about how to speak again about women and sexuality in this new cultural context. what has changed in me, in us, and all around us? i can feel my new work beginning to answer this call.... )#avian #ceramicsculpture #figurativeart #figuresculpture #contemporaryart #sculpture #birdskulls #skull #avianart #beautifulbizarre #clay

text:
i wish words like "gay", "straight", "male", "female", "black", or "white" didn't exist when referring to creatures. how about we replace those words with one, "living". i hate that when talking about some of my friends i have to say "my gay friends" or "they're also gay". or anything like that, why for some people do i need to specify what gender they prefer to love? or if they love any gender? or if they love both? can't i just say "yeah, this is my friend, they're a nice person, they keep on living like the rest of us, despite the harsh route "god" has sent all of us down. but hey, nobody said the road to happiness was easy. the most we can do is try." if you're triggered by me putting god in quotes it's just cause not everyone believes in him and there's no real way to know that's actually the name of whatever's up there. i try not to side with any religion in my posts because i honestly don't follow the rules of just one. if you wanna rant to me about how me saying god may not be real at all please do so privately so it doesn't disturb others but do keep in mind i will be reporting you if anything you say becomes violent at any point. 
looked into #metoo cause i was curious as to what people actually put there. it's exactly what i expected. people telling their stories and stuff like that. some were sad, i won't deny it but a lot of the posts were kinda random. 
the picture is my lock screen right now! i'll be changing it to rainbow soon though cause black and white is kinda boring after a bit.

the picture is my lock screen right now! i'll be changing it to rainbow soon though cause black and white is kinda boring after a bit.

text:
â¤©
my truth 
was buried alive
it's no wonder
when you touch me
i cannot breathe
.
touch is such a beautiful & necessary expression of love. i'm tired of my body feeling like a battlefield.
it is difficult retraining these perceptions. i'm becoming more aware of the resistance in my physical form; mainly concerning touch. intellectually, i know that not all forms of human touch are of sexual nature, yet instinctually my body recoils or resists if anyone, even friends, simply try to hold my hand, rub my shoulders or even hug me. there is a moment that i freeze up or tremble, feeling familiar fight or flight adrenaline & my midwest mentality races to find a way to reject it politely. this fear doesn't really feel like "me" in the moment.. but an animal defense mechanism. how prey must feel. i take a moment to breathe and try to tell my body it is safe & to melt into it. sometimes i do, sometimes i don't. i know i'm not alone in this, i know women who have similar experiences.
regardless of gender, we all have a story. #metoo
it's tricky digging out these tender, tangled roots in my system and planting new seeds when i'm so far from the arms of the ones who make me feel safe, [â™¡] but out here there is no tip-toeing to my core.. or testing the warmth of the water.
i'll hold close my courage.
& jump.
.
.

i recently answered a dm where someone wasnâ€™t sure if their partner was a narcissist. iâ€™m not a therapist, i donâ€™t know these people and i certainly am not qualified to diagnose anyoneâ€”even if i were, again, i havenâ€™t met them! (although in certain circumstances personal experience > education and i certainly think no one can truly talk about what narcissistic abuse does to someone at a certain level unless theyâ€™ve personally experienced the hell that is being involved with someone like this.) .
.
with all of this being said, unfairly labeling someone isnâ€™t cool either!! itâ€™s hurtful and insulting to call someone bipolar, another anorexic, someone else emotionally disregulated and another person clinically depressed when they arenâ€™t. well itâ€™s rude to label someone as npd when they arenâ€™t either!! it isnâ€™t fair to the person being labeled and it takes away from the true, awful abuse that victims experience from actual narcissists. know the signs. .
.
someone who takes a lot of selfies isnâ€™t narcissistic in a lot of cases. maybe he/she is comfortable with who they are? maybe we could take self love lessons from them! another who talks about only themselves isnâ€™t necessarily one either! maybe theyâ€™re nervous and not good at speaking to groups so they talk about what they knowâ€”themselves! .
.
stop labeling unless you know. and if youâ€™re not sure, educate yourself, read several different reliable sources, talk to fighters/survivors, make a list if you have to. incorrectly labeling someone is not fair nor is it right!

text:
copies of garden, our self-printed booklet of #poems and #illustrations inspired by and written for #survivors of abuse, rape and trauma will be available in exchange for donations on tuesday 11th at the christmas fayre, eldon building, university of portsmouth.

garden has received an excellent review here https://theeldonreview.wordpress.com/2018/12/02/review-of-garden-by-anna-and-tessa-foley/

excerpt here: the inclusion of enchanting pictures alongside the poems rescues some beauty from pain. these are visual metaphors for the identities of survivors who will not allow their victimhood to define them. the poem â€˜youâ€™ uses this conceit in a particularly moving way, its tone of ambiguity about whether the damage done is lasting â€“ â€˜you walk a stride each day and nightâ€™ â€“ counterposed by the picture of a gorgeous flower.

all proceeds will go to portsmouth abuse and rape counselling service. 
#metoo #timesup #yourvoicematters #sexualabuse #domesticabuse  #rapesurvivor #portsmouth #poetry

text:
the #metoo movement began in 2017, which encouraged women who had experienced sexual assault or sexual harassment to come forward with their experiences on social media to showcase how common this experience is. this particular social media movement resulted in an overwhelming increase in dialogue about this issue. this image reflects the empowerment women felt as they were invited to share their experiences of sexual harassment or assault without the traditional stigma attached to it. 
negar mottahedah attempts to explain the origin of the hashtag in his book #iranelection: hashtag solidarity and the transformation of online life. he says the hashtag was used â€œas a way to create groups, the hashtag became an aggregator, a way to research a topic, and by bringing focus and attention to posted content, a way to measure the range and popularity of a topic on the social media platform.â€ although she was not the first to use the hashtag, alyssa milano popularized #metoo on twitter, leading to the viral campaign. this practice of hashtag activism gave women a sense of belonging, and attempted to make the discussion of sexual assault and harassment normal through empowerment. 
mottahedah described the connection formed on twitter through hashtags as an â€œemergence of [a] shared revolutionary consciousnessâ€, which i think described the general attitude of the #metoo movement (pg 31). the women who participated in the hashtag were building a revolutionary consciousness surrounding an issue which was largely concealed in the past. this image depicts a woman using a megaphone to shout #metoo, which i think is an appropriate analogy to how the #metoo movement exploded online.

#militarizationandrebellioninthevisualsphere #citizenjournalism #hashtagactivism #metoo
#visualculturecarolinafall2018

@visualculturecarolina

text:
i normally do not get political on social media nor do i feel being passive aggressive on such platforms helps my case but something needs to be said so allow me to be a smidge hypocritical for a couple of minutes. 
i saw a post today that i disagree with wholeheartedly. some of you know the reason and others will find out when itâ€™s the right time but i have a huge problem with the assumption that sexual crimes happen because a person looks a certain way. i understand it to be very different. rape never happens for a reason, other than the psycho doing it lacking empathy, morality and a respect for other people who are (more often than not) in your life. to blame what happens on the victim, for any reason, is wrong. nobody asks for this. #metoo

text:
#metoo ðŸ˜ž
i feel ya girl.
.
remember when the whole â€œme tooâ€ movement began and it felt like there was finally a safe space to speak out? you felt less alone and realized you were actually supported.
.
you emerged from the shadows to join the ranks of countless women who were in a similar position.
.
but then time passed and things got pushed under the rug again.
.
maybe you spoke up to some people, felt free and had a momentary release... but then it was over.
.
you returned to carrying the burden, the guilt, and the shame.
.
it seemed like it was just expected of you to move on with ease.
.
â€œwell you got it off your chest (no pun intended) so now itâ€™s back to normal, right?â€ -says someone whose never experienced it.
.
wrong!!
.
things donâ€™t just magically disappear like that. ðŸ™…ðŸ¼â€â™€ï¸
.
negative energy around trauma and a deep loss of control/privacy doesnâ€™t just float away into the clouds.
.
you have to do more.
.
that was just the first step - and a huge, inspiring, powerful one at that - but the journey to freedom takes more.
. . .
last week i opened up on a podcast about sexual assault and how i was stuck in some negative patterns.
.
i didnâ€™t feel worthy enough to deserve better and i definitely didnâ€™t feel strong enough to speak up or tell people to stop treating me that way.
.
looking back i can see the error of my ways, and how i was playing small. and when you play small - it can be easy to become a target.
.
in no way am i blaming myself or blaming women in these situations - but i have come to see the power i couldâ€™ve had if iâ€™d truly believed in myself back then. we are all so much stronger than we know!
.
i canâ€™t wait for you to hear my podcast interview (coming soon!) but until then iâ€™m going to be using the next few posts to share some of my story and the things i learned through sexual assault.
.
iâ€™m here with ya girl, i know the pain youâ€™re carrying, the negative energy youâ€™ve got bottled up inside.
.
and iâ€™m here to help you release it. please shoot me a dm if you want my help. iâ€™ve helped multiple clients work through their own sexual assaults and find freedom and clarity. and iâ€™d love to help you do the same ðŸ™ðŸ¼ðŸ’•

text:
my rapist is back in town....
or still in town. he left years ago and i didnt know he moved back. he was arrested for a dui last night and attacked my brother-in-law who was the booking officer. 
my mother called to tell me. when she said his name my heart jumped into my throat and i couldn't breathe. the tears immediately started pouring down. 
i hate myself for not pressing charges long ago...but it's too late now.. i feel terrified. i feel like i have no control. i want to gorge myself to take away this pain. i feel weak. i dont want to be alone right now....

text:
equilibrium
--
you didn't just leave. 
i had to erase you from my mind
from my fingers and bones,
from my cracked ribs that held a broken heart, still beating...
.
.
.
you didn't just leave, 
you made me fight with every thought of yours,
every voice inside my head was your voice... .
.
.
you didn't just leave, you made me your shadow! 
i had to look for me, 
i was buried deep under the piles of your garbage words that i allowed in. 
how could i ever believe you? .
.
oh! why didn't you just leave
with all your belongings? 
why do i have to keep cleaning up after you.
one  piece of letter here, one cloth there, some thoughts on the floor, some on the ceiling.
.
.
why the hell did you not just leave,
 forever, at once?
you left in waves...
and sometimes i still see bits of you.
.
.
but you know what,
my crests and troughs are becoming smaller and smaller. 
i am about to reach equilibrium 
and your voices, your thoughts, your energies, your visions will just be something i lived through.
.
.
and i am going to be grateful for this, 
yes, i am going to one day look back and realise, you were my gift, my turning point, my decider for the road less traveled and my tipping point! .
. ~
zenona
..
------
i once fell as if i will never rise but i did rise and now i know the way to show my fellow fallers! 
remember it's okay to fall. but its not okay to stay there! 
get up! move along... don't crowd the road. there are others behind you that need you to keep moving! .
.

text: â€œiâ€™m very pleased and proud to loan a piece of my artwork to @ymcanorfolk stepping stones cafe in norwich today. art has provided me a way in which to tackle some very difficult and dark moments in my life. and i hope that people visiting stepping stones can look at my work and find a glimmer of hope in whatever struggles they may be facing themselves. for me, itâ€™s never been about just selling paintings. but about providing hope to those who feel lost and alone. after 14 years iâ€™ve finally found my â€˜voiceâ€™. i hope everyone visiting and working at stepping stones finds theirs.â€ - jamie. #art #artist #abstract #abstractart #creative #visualarts #norfolk #norwich #ymca #ymcanorfolk #charity #depression #mentalhealth #metoo #norfolkart #norfolkartist #raw #energy #emotionalcontent #artoninstagram #artchangesthings #thinkdifferent #paint #acrylic #canvas #artiststakerisks

text:
[read caption below ðŸ‘‡]
.
you know what's wrong? doing something wrong and thinking its cool, because there's no guilt, for the only reason that boys don't think about it. and today i'm specifically talking about boys.
-
so i was playing with couple of randoms and they were having a talk about some girl. they were like, i wish she was here, would have fucked her.
-
i have no shame in bringing out what many boys talk about, but i do feel sorry for the double standards we show.
let another guy talk like that about our sister and we will kill that guy, is what we say.
-
a girl, is a human like you, has a body like you and emotions like you, and she is being treated like nothing but a sex object by one else than you. that single statement defines your ethics, morality and values, the person you are and what you think.
-
it means nothing by sharing "respect girls" quotes on facebook and instagram if this is what you think about any girl.
-
me, as a guy, take a pledge to change this thing about my friends. i will stop them from talking such things about any girl, known or unknown.
.
slowly, i hope things will change, the words will change and maybe someday the views will also change.
.
tag your friends and take a pledge today so that each one of you could proudly save that i brought a change!
.
.

text:
blame abuser not neo tantra

iâ€™ve been thinking a lot of what is going on in the tantra community and i am frustrated at the fact that some people are trying to blame neo tantra for all the abuse and rapes in tantra. i donâ€™t see it that way. i see it as people, individuals whether they are in or out of tantra, they are the ones responsible for their actions.

so many want to blame anyone or anything but the people that are responsible. like my mother who wanted to blame herself because of some abuse i went through when i was youngâ€¦she blamed herself, when i told her it wasnâ€™t her fault she said â€œthen why did you let it happenâ€? she couldnâ€™t conceive that this wasnâ€™t hers or my fault, that it was the person who did the abuse.

well it is not tantraâ€™s fault for the abuse. it is an easy way to get people naked and then abuse people. but it is not tantra, it is the practitioners themselves. when i look at the list of people who have been much of the abuse in the tantra world, they have some association with source school of tantra. that makes sense as when the owner of a school crosses boundaries, and many follow suit. and, not all have. i know many students from them who havenâ€™t crossed boundaries, though many of those are women, and i have known women from source that have gone beyond what we are taught and shown in our training. and i know people from other schools and lineages that cross boundaries and abuse, so it is not all source too. 
i will take a guess that people do this as it has been done to them in a session with a teacher or they had it in them anyway. abuse and prostitution is not part of tantra, it is rape or prostitution. or it is being a sex surrogate, but again, that is not tantra. and i am not against prostitution or sex surrogacy, i am against people saying they are doing tantra but what they really are doing is something elseâ€¦hand jobs, release, sex surrogacy or prostitution. just call it what it is, donâ€™t put it under the guise of â€œtantraâ€. i spoke to one of the main assistants at source tantra a few years ago and she said â€œi donâ€™t know how you can not have sex with your clients, i just donâ€™t know 
cont below
#metoo #metoowithdakas #tantra

text:
as the most oscar-nominated actress in the history, meryl streep has won 3 of the 19 oscar and 8 of the 27 golden globes nominations. her ability to carry any roles with grace, style, and panache. she has brought each of the characters she played alive on screen and has mesmerized the audience with her power-packed acting. 
she has been vocal about women issues and gender equality. she is the national spokesperson for the national woman's history museum which aims to inform the public and encourage sexual equality. 
sanfe salutes meryl streep, who continues to enthral all of us with her acting prowess.
 we wish that more and more women will take a leaf out of her book and get inspired to #standupforyourself and up for not just themselves but others too.

text:
joan crawford visiting myrna loy on the set of 'man-proof' with j. edgar hooverÂ and clyde tolson, 1938.
.
an excerpt from loy's autobiography being and becoming:

bob mcintyre gave me a consolation prize, a job in pretty ladies. that's when i first met joan crawford. we were both chorus girls in this thing, which starred zasu pitts and tom moore and featured norma shearer, conrad nagel, and a lot of people impersonating ziegfeld follies stars. it's amazing to think that norma, joan, and i would all become rather important to mgm in later years. and here we were, joan and i these two little extras, as part of a human chandelier. they had us hanging on to this thing with our toes out, all of these girls going in different directions. it was a riot.

joan had been signed to a contract, and she was living on nothing but black coffee to slim down for the camera. she was still lucille le sueur then. they ran a contest after pretty ladies to find her a new name. oh, she was wonderful! she was learning all the new dances, black bottom, charleston, and urging me to go down to the ambassador and do them with her. being such a snob about dance, of course, i wouldn't have any part of it. but that's what made her a star, later on, in our dancing daughters.

one day, joan came into the dressing room looking very unhappy. she fell into my lap - and she began to cry. joan always worried terribly. i did, too, but never showed it. apparently, harry rapf, the producer who discovered her, had chased her around the desk the night before. she was having a terrible time. she had such a beautiful body that they were all after her. i didn't have quite that much trouble - my sort of snooty attitude put them off a bit.
.
â†ªï¸#joanmetrogoldwynmayer

text: #metoo in pakistan 1970s ðŸ˜‚ðŸ‘ - hilarious. this video will make you laugh till your stomach hurts. the 'me too' movement did not gather much steam in pakistan vs neighbouring india in 2018. however more than 40 years ago, in the 1970s this super hit pakistani film 'shabana' (1976) addressed the issue of women being sexually harassed at work by their male bosses. pakistani media and films were not into the 'bechari aurat'/'women are helpless victims' narrative & mindset at that time and seem to have a more progressive approach to the subject. the heroine in the movie proactively deals with her evil boss, who regularly gets female office staff drunk at office parties to abuse & molest them. instead of falling victim to his evil plans, she tries to strangle him, shoots at him with a gun, & slaps the living day lights out of him. ðŸ˜‚ðŸ˜‚ the entire film is about fighting off these unwelcome advances by men at the workplace. the movie created a box office record and completed more than 100 days at the cinemas in 1976. #metoo #metoopakistan #1970s #karachi #karachicityoflights #pakistan #citybythesea

text:
screenshots of a conversation between russian designerÂ gosha rubchinskiyÂ and a 16-year-old male fan surfaced on several social media pages this week. these screenshots show the designer asking the boy for images and telling him to take pictures in the bathroom to avoid his parents finding out.Â the screenshots initially appeared onÂ @hftgroupÂ and were  then posted across other fashion-focused accounts. the russian designer, responded by stating that it was for a casting call. however, since then the 16 year old released facetime footage, suggesting otherwise. i've read several articles and posts on this issue and it's amazing that some attempted to justify the behavior between and adult designer and a minor by saying, russian's age of consent is 16 years old. but, i believe the laws prohibit sexual pictures in russia.
gosha is known for bringing youth culture and has featured russian teens in several of his fashionÂ shows. in the us because of documented child sexual abuse (csa), we have underage modeling laws. one is the modelsâ€™ harassment protection act, which was introduced by a former child model. however in other countries laws are minimal & have a lot of grey areas. this topic was brought to the forefront during the #metoo movement by several fashion ppl, of which many were unsure if anything could be done in the fashion industry. how do we protect these teens in fashion? 
as i stated before, speaking to your children and even learning about sexual health as an adult, can be a protection against sexual abuse and improving your sexual health. those who have or had a csa history have greater risk of experiencing more adverse outcomes, including risky sexual behaviors, sexual problems, and negative sexual self-concept.Â we must continue to speak out about sexual abuse in the fashion industries as we do in other areas. 
#preventionmeetsfashion #fashion #sexualhealth #sexeducation #socialworker #sexeducator #sexualabuse

text:
setelah memenangkan penghargaan di ffi 2015 lalu dan beberapa penghargaan festival film di luar negeri, film siti karya eddie cahyono akan kembali diputar di hari terakhir enam belas film festival bali!

film yang kental dengan isu perempuan di masyarakat ini juga menggambarkan seseorang yang bimbang akan pilihannya hidupnya. lalu bagaimanakah kelanjutan kisah siti? saksikan hanya di enam belas film festival bali pada closing night, yang akan dimeriahkan oleh acoustic performance dari penyanyi dan penulis lagu berdarah filipina-amerika @sandrayatifay diikuti penampilan teater oleh @teaterkalangan.

hari: senin, 10 desember 2018
jam: registrasi dibuka pukul 16.00 wita
venue: cushcush gallery, jalan teuku umar gg. rajawali 1a, denpasar

festival ini gratis dan jangan lupa membawa tumbler/botol sendiri, karena acara ini berkomitmen zerowaste.

sampai jumpa di closing night #enambelasffestbali!

#hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali #saveibunuril #zerowasteevent #zerowastebali

text:
i too have a story to share.

this one's is about the woman i started following on instagram. natasha noel. @natashanoel001 .
.
she's a motivational speaker and also a yogini. her posts and videos are exactly what every human who is broken somewhere from inside needs to hear desperately. her words are so powerful and inspiring, that just a small video or reading the caption of any of her random post makes me feel more confident about myself. and what's more amazing is that she herself is healing. she herself is a survivor of childhood abuse.

she is a live example of the beautiful quote - "you can be both a masterpiece and a work in progress simultaneously." keep smiling and wish you loads of happiness in life. .
- from swarada @d_arcane_pneuma
.
.
.................................................................
.

in these times of #metoo and stories of sexual harassment, there are also women and men around us who made us feel more beautiful, more confident and powerful from both inside and out. 
if there is such a person in your life who ever made you feel so about yourself then wait no longer and share your story too. let us pay a small tribute to her/him here @shespeaksforthechange.

we all need such people around us afterall, don't we?
(dm us your story or tag us in your post.) _______________________________________

#yogini #loveyourself #inspiration #motivation

#shespeaksforthechange

text:
grace brewster murray hopper (december 9, 1906 â€“ january 1, 1992) was an american computer scientist and united states navy rear admiral.
one of the first programmers of the harvard mark i computer, she was a pioneer of computer programming who invented one of the first compiler related tools.
she popularized the idea of machine-independent programming languages, which led to the development of cobol, an early high-level programming language.
prior to joining the navy, hopper attained a ph.d. in mathematics from yale university and was a professor of mathematics at vassar college.
in 1949, she joined the eckertâ€“mauchly computer corporation and was part of the team that developed the univac i computer.
her compiler converted english terms into machine code understood by computers.
in 1954, eckertâ€“mauchly chose hopper to lead their department for automatic programming, and she led the release of some of the first compiled languages like flow-matic.
in 1959, she participated in the codasyl consortium, which consulted hopper to guide them in creating a machine-independent programming language.
this led to the cobol language, which was inspired by her idea of a language being based on english words.
owing to her accomplishments and her naval rank, she was sometimes referred to as "amazing grace".
the u.s. navy arleigh burke-class guided-missile destroyer uss hopper was named for her, as was the cray xe6 "hopper" supercomputer at nersc.
during her lifetime, hopper was awarded 40 honorary degrees from universities across the world.
a college at yale university was renamed in her honor.
in 1991, she received the national medal of technology.
on november 22, 2016, she was posthumously awarded the presidential medal of freedom by president barack obama.

text:
talent jumo is a passionate feminist activist from zimbabwe. a teacher by profession, talent has 13 yearsâ€™ experience working on women and health programmes, particularly on sexual and reproductive health and rights, including hiv and aids. talent co-founded the young womenâ€™s leadership initiative (now katswe sistahood) in 2007, and has served katswe sistahood as director since 2012. katswe sistahood, winner of the 2015 stars global with and for girls award, has championed the agenda for movement-building with young women from marginalised communities in zimbabwe towards the achievement of their sexual and reproductive health rights. in her work, talent has prioritised rights of young women and adolescent girls from marginalised groups, including sex workers, and advocated for social protection for sexually exploited children. 
in 2016, talent was nominated to serve as the womenâ€™s representative on the country coordinating mechanism against hiv/tb and malaria, through the womenâ€™s coalition of zimbabwe- health cluster. she is a member of the women for the global fund. in 2017, talent became a member of the ngo delegation to the global fund against hiv, tb and malaria. talent is also the current chair of the right here right now (zimbabwe platform), a strategic partnership that envisions a world where young people, in all their diversity, acquire full and uninterrupted access to comprehensive sexuality education, and youth-friendly sexual and reproductive health services, including safe abortion. (words adapted from https://www.120under40.org/nominee/talent-jumo)

text:
in pakistan, the common misconception is that women are not qualified enough to do what men can. only 3 percent are employed in the formal sector, with most of those crowded into historically low-paying, female-dominated jobs. pakistan is the second worst country when it comes to gender equality in the global gender gap index.

text:
i am organising an event in january that aims to demystify some of the things you may think vthe word feminism means and discuss the importance of why feminism as a movement is so important to the future of our society. 
this event is for anyone whatever understanding you already have about feminism. you may feel like all the chatter in the media about #metoo etc is confusing and doesnâ€™t relate to you or you may feel like you have lots of ideas and thoughts that we would love to hear!

i am looking to have a panel of people willing to answer questions and talk on pre agreed topics. if you would like to contribute and/or be on the panel please let me know in the comments below. iâ€™d particularly like to hear from women of colour, lgbtq people and women with disabilities as i feel this will give us the best opportunity to discuss a wide range of topics. donâ€™t feel you have to be super qualified to speak. it will be a supportive environment and the main thing we want is to allow everyone who wants, to share their experiences.

we are hoping the event will take place in witney on a sunday afternoon in january (currently looking like 20th). any comments about what youâ€™d like to hear about would also be welcome below! 
#feminism #equality #feminist #demystifyingfeminism #thiscenturyisours #intersectionalfeminism #changeforgood #womensupportingwomen #events #eventsforfeminism #discussions #wep

text:
"what if instead of drugging, shocking, tying down our mad women, we put them in warm tubs of water naked as babies and got in there with them and cooed and encouraged them to cry great salt tears, to grieve the passing of dreams, the rape of the soul? what if we rocked them to sleep in giant hammocks of competent fat arms when they were too damn exhausted with keeping up pretenses or holding up their heads any longer? what if we agreed with her that the whole world is fucking crazy, out of balance, and that she is not to blame for the halt and the lame, the lack of food, the phone not being answered, the port wine stains on babies, the wars on every continent of the globe?
what if we gave her a baseball bat (none of this nerf shit, impotent, harm none, foam battaca bat bullshit, but a solid wood bone-cracking put a goddamn lump on it base - fucking - ball bat) and let her slam every post, stump, wall, door, window, house, and car in an arena where she is cheered on to a frenzy? then letâ€™s pick her up when she falls down exhausted and foaming and take her down to the locker room for a steam bath and a massage that leave her noodle limp and rage-less for the first time in decades.â€ ......and then, after she slept, and dreamt her world into being, she awoke in all her glory, adorned with jewels, sacred oils and stardust, and stood arms outstretched, face stoic, heart fierce and gave the same gift of healing to the men that love her. we're all part of the scar clan...we support eachother. #metoo #newmoonmagic #sacredmasculine #sacredfeminine #growthfromthemostunlikelyofplaces #warriorclan #medicinetribe #dark #wet #wild #messy #tangled #blessed #followtheleprechaun #thereisgoldinsideher

text:
â€œmy issue is that when good men talk about bad men, they always ignore the line in the sand â€” the line in the sand that is inevitably drawn whenever a good man talks about bad men: â€œi am a good man. here is the line. there are all the bad men.â€ the jimmys and the good men wonâ€™t talk about this line, but we really need to talk about this line. letâ€™s call it kevin. and letâ€™s never call it that again. we need to talk about how men will draw a different line for every different occasion. they have a line for the locker room; a line for when their wives, mothers, daughters, and sisters are watching; another line for when theyâ€™re drunk and fratting; another line for nondisclosure; a line for friends; and a line for foes. you know why we need to talk about this line between good men and bad men? because itâ€™s only good men who get to draw that line. and guess what? all men believe they are good. we need to talk about this because guess what happens when only good men get to draw that line? this world â€” a world full of good men who do very bad things and still believe in their heart of hearts that they are good men because they have not crossed the line, because they move the line for their own good. women should be in control of that line, no question.

now take everything i have said up until this point and replace â€œmanâ€ with â€œwhite person,â€ and know that if you are a white woman, you have no place drawing lines in the sand between good white people and bad white people. i encourage you to also take the time to replace â€œmanâ€ with â€œstraightâ€ or â€œcisâ€ or â€œable-bodiedâ€ or â€œneurotypical,â€ et cetera, et cetera. everybody believes they are fundamentally good, and we all need to believe we are fundamentally good because believing you are fundamentally good is part of the human condition. but if you have to believe someone else is bad in order to believe you are good, you are drawing a very dangerous line. in many ways, these lines in the sand we all draw are stories we tell to ourselves so we can still believe we are good people.â€

text:
itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: our head of contacts @lynongod making her contribution at the interactive discussion during the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
âš¡ï¸ sahkan segera rancangan undang-undang penghapusan kekerasan seksual âš¡ï¸
.
indonesia telah gagal melindungi korban kekerasan seksual secara hukum!
. 
sejak tahun 2012, ruu p-ks hanya tergeletak di atas meja â€œwakil rakyatâ€ kami di dpr, sehingga kasus-kasus seperti ibu nuril, agni, tuti trusilawati dan yang lainnya kerap bermunculan tanpa diakhiri dengan keadilan yang semestinya. menurut data @komnasperempuan, 35 orang perempuan menjadi korban kekerasan seksual setiap harinya. ini menunjukkan bahwa indonesia darurat dalam menangani kasus korban kekerasan seksual yang telah menjamur di negeri ini!
.
8 desember 2018 kemarin, bersama @sistersindanger, @simponi_id, dan banyak grup/aktivis lainnya dari berbagai kalangan (gender, ham, agamis), kami berjalan menuju depan istana untuk menuntut rancangan undang-undang penghapusan kekerasan seksual segera disahkan! #gerakbersama #metoo #hearmetoo #16haktp
.
p.s. saya tidak tergabung dengan fatayat nu, hanya memegang posternya...

âœ” áƒ¤áƒ˜áƒšáƒ›áƒ˜áƒ¡ áƒ©áƒ•áƒ”áƒœáƒ”áƒ‘áƒ áƒ’áƒáƒ˜áƒ›áƒáƒ áƒ—áƒ”áƒ‘áƒ áƒ“áƒ¦áƒ”áƒ¡, 9 áƒ“áƒ”áƒ™áƒ”áƒ›áƒ‘áƒ”áƒ áƒ¡, 14:00 áƒ¡áƒáƒáƒ—áƒ–áƒ”, áƒáƒ›áƒ˜áƒ áƒáƒœáƒ˜áƒ¡ áƒ™áƒ˜áƒœáƒáƒ—áƒ”áƒáƒ¢áƒ áƒ¨áƒ˜. â€¢

â€¢ ðŸ“¢ðŸ‡ªðŸ‡ºðŸŽ¥ the sixth film to be nominated for this year's 'eu human rights in film award' is the italian/franch co-production 'womanâ€™s name', directed by marco tullio giordana.
ðŸŽ¬ the film was in fact conceived over three years ago and focuses on the issue of sexual harassment in the workplace. in the era of #metoo and #timesup, and a renewed awareness of the dignity of women in the face of subversive harassment and discrimination, giordana's film arrives as a manifesto of rebellion. it's a story of nina, a young woman who moves to a small village in lower lombardy with her daughter and finds a job in a prestigious private hospital where many other women, both italian and foreign, also work. this small, ragtag community of females is nevertheless very much united - by a secret, among other things.
âœ” the film will be screened today, 9 december, at 14:00, in amirani theatre.

text:
i can only speak for myself, but 30 is not the new 20. 30 is 30, and thank god for that. feeling very grateful for all the incredible adventures i've been blessed to have in my life thus far.  for whatever reasons, this is a big birthday for me. i know social media can create an image of unrealistic utopia, so i'd like to temper that with some real hard knocks i learned (the hard way) over my last 2 decades: 
1. it's ok to celebrate myself!
2. i'm manic depressive with mild ocd. feels good to say it out loud.
3. once you find the right therapist, they are worth every frickin penny. 
4. i am not required to apologize, for anything, ever. 
5. i have physical and emotional boundaries and the right to protect them. #metoo
6. it's alllll about perspective - check yo filter.
7. i will never have it all figured out.
8. i was born to sing to all of you.

what did you learn from your 20s, or what are you learning still?? tell me, i love you,  xoxo gracie

happy weekend!

when it was first published, fat is a feminist issue became an instant classic and it is as relevant today as it was then. reflecting on our increasingly diet and body-obsessed society, susie orbachâ€™s new introduction explains how generations of women and girls are growing up absorbing the eating anxieties around them. in an age where women want to be sexy, nurturing, domestic goddesses, confident at work, and feminine too, the twenty-first-century woman is poorly armed for survival. never before has the fat is a feminist issue revolution been more in need of revival.

exploring our love/hate relationship with food, susie orbach describes how fat is about so much more than food. it is a response to our social situation; the way we are seen by others and ourselves. too often food is a source of anguish, as are our bodies. but fat is a feminist issue discusses how we can turn food into a friend and find ways to accept ourselves for who and how we are. following the step-by-step guide, and you too can put an end to food anxieties and dieting.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words, every day.

the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and keep abusing the faith of their fellow men. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

dear america, me me me finnish ass can't do more than this.

text:
it has been heavy on my heart to share about respect. specifically in the realm of speaking out... our culture is very aware of #metoo #timesup #whyididntreport and #womensreality 
i always have admiration for these people who have been directly affected by situations that would inspire them to speak out, huge respect! i never realized the impact that stepping out and sharing has. both positive and negative.
our culture is all about speaking out- bringing light to what was done and hope that through due process, justice will be found. i am a big supporter of this truth telling. i never really understood the blowback that could occur once you've made that huge step to speak out. i never fully understood the risk until i was faced with the option to speak out.
i think as humans we need to respect people. respect doesn't mean you agree. it means you honor their decision. you don't have to support, you can respect and disagree at the same time. 
in this culture of "speak out" we lack the pieces to fully support those once they do. i see people turn around and attack them instead. 
what i've experienced is people either come together and support you. completely belittle your decision and experience and disregard you, or think that their idea of what happen is truth and share your story in a negative light, taking your hardship and running it through the mud. 
i see respect a lacking pillar in humanity these days and i am heart broken. i am not sure what to do about it, because respect needs to be modeled, taught, and learned. it takes more than social media. we need pillars of hope, truth and love in our communities.... we need leaders. 
#culture #respect #speakout #truth #support #bethechangeyouwanttosee #teachthenextgeneration #raisethemstrong #ispokeout

ah, my sweet aya necklace. â£
â£
ayahuasca really reminds me of sound healing and breathwork in so many ways. aya gives you what you need. sometimes what you need and what you want arenâ€™t aligned and you realize this after. so does breathwork and sound healing. both shed layers of ego and peel back societal expectations. you are given clarity about your own truth instead of getting lost in trying to please others. â£
â£
both can let you explore your trauma with compassion and clarity so you may have the steps to move forward. it can be dark but ever so healing. the exploration is brave if nothing else. â£
â£
sound healing and breathwork can personally bring me to similar realms as aya. it all depends on if iâ€™m feeling like going off the grid for the great purge. when you feel the call, you donâ€™t ignore it. â£
â£
my prayer is for my body to be safe after what just happened. my intention is to find trust again after a deep betrayal of having my choice taken away. i want to have the courage to take what happened and use it to speak up and make change happen so that others can seek justice safely.
â£
thank you to the #metoomovement without all of your bravery, it would be hard to find mine. â£
â£
i will update post-ceremony. â£
â£
aho!â£
â£
